Singleton is one of the most important Creational Design Patterns in Java.


1. What is singleton pattern?
--Singleton Pattern ensures that only one object (instance) of a class is created in the entire application and provides a global access point to use that object.

2. Core Rules of Singleton
--A Singleton class usually has:
   1.Private constructor → no outside object creation
   2.Static instance variable → stores single object
   3.Public static method → returns same object

3. Ways to make a class Singleton
--Eager initialization
--Lazy initialization
--Thread-safe initialization
--Double check initialization

4. Eager Initialization Singleton
--Object is created immediately when class is loaded by JVM.
--Instance is stored in static variable.
--Thread-safe because class loading is thread-safe in Java.
--Simple implementation.
--Disadvantage: object is created even if never used.

5. Lazy Initialization Singleton
--Object is not created at class loading time.
--Created only when first request comes.
--Saves memory because object is created on demand.
--Disadvantage: basic lazy version is not thread-safe.

6. Thread-Safe Singleton
--Used to solve issue of multiple threads creating multiple objects.
--getInstance() method is synchronized.
--Only one thread can enter method at a time.
--Advantage: thread-safe.
--Disadvantage: slower performance due to synchronization.

7. Double Checked Locking Singleton
--Used for better performance with thread safety.
--Checks instance two times:
   1.Before synchronization
   2.After synchronization
--Locking happens only when object is null.
--Uses volatile keyword.

8. Why volatile is used?
--Ensures latest value is visible to all threads.
--Prevents instruction reordering by JVM.
--Avoids partially initialized object creation.
--Used mainly in multithreading environment.
--Variable value is read from main memory, not stale CPU cache.
--Provides visibility guarantee between threads.
--Mostly used in Double Checked Locking Singleton.
--Does not provide atomicity for operations like count++.
--Used for flags, status variables, shutdown signals.
--Improves correctness in concurrent programs.

Example 1:
volatile boolean running = true;

Thread 1:
while(running){
   // work
}

Thread 2:
running = false;

--Thread 1 immediately sees updated value and stops loop.

Example 2:
private static volatile Singleton instance;

--Used in Double Checked Locking Singleton.
--Ensures all threads get fully initialized Singleton object.

9. Why private constructor is needed?
--Prevents object creation using new keyword outside class.
--Maintains only one object rule.
--Provides controlled instantiation.

10. Why static instance variable is needed?
--Static belongs to class, not object.
--Only one copy exists in memory.
--Shared by all users of class.

11. Why static getInstance() method is needed?
--Allows access without creating object.
--Returns same Singleton instance every time.
--Provides global access point.

12. OOP Concepts Used in Singleton
--Encapsulation:
   Constructor made private to control object creation.
--Abstraction:
   User only calls getInstance(), internal creation hidden.
--Static Members:
   Shared class-level object.

13. Advantages of Singleton
--Only one object created.
--Saves memory.
--Global access point.
--Useful for shared resources.
--Controlled lifecycle of object.

14. Disadvantages of Singleton
--Hard to test because global state.
--Can create tight coupling.
--May violate Single Responsibility Principle.
--Thread-safe implementation can be complex.

15. Real World Examples
--Logger
--Configuration Manager
--Cache Manager
--Database Connection Manager
--Printer Spooler
--Runtime class in Java

16. How Singleton Can Be Broken
--Reflection:
   Can access private constructor.
--Serialization:
   Deserialization may create new object.
--Cloning:
   clone() may create duplicate object.
--Multiple Class Loaders:
   Same class loaded separately may create multiple instances.

17. Best Safe Singleton in Java
--Enum Singleton

Reason:
--Thread-safe
--Serialization-safe
--Reflection-safe
--Simple syntax

18. When to Use Singleton
--When exactly one object is required.
--When shared access is needed.
--When centralized control is needed.

19. When to Avoid Singleton
--When multiple instances may be needed later.
--When dependency injection framework is used.
--When unit testing and mocking are required.

20. Interview One Line Answer
--Singleton Pattern ensures only one instance of a class exists and provides a global access point using private constructor and static access method.

